<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-305-612  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 305 612.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  April 5 1990 v139 pC8(N) pD12(L) 14 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Surprise hurts Oracle Systems. (Market Place) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fisher, Lawrence M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Oracle Systems Corp will post earnings per share of 18 cents forits quarter ended Feb 28, 1990 on earnings of $24.3 million.andP;  Sixdays before announcing the earnings, Oracle told financialanalysts that earnings per share would be between 23 and 25 centsper share.andP;  Wall Street responded to the news of the actualearnings by dumping a record number of shares in the company,resulting in a drop of $7.875 per share to $17.50 on Mar 29, 1990.andO;Oracle attributes the lower earnings to $15 million in salesdisallowed by auditors on Mar 23.andP;  Because software contracts atOracle are sold on a trial basis, there is some question aboutwhen a sale can be counted.andP;  Oracle says the confusion has beenresolved, and this will be the only quarter affected.andP;  Analystsare beginning to question the quality of Oracle's management:there has been an increase in accounts receivable and rumors ofquality control problems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Oracle Systems Corp. (finance).andO;Ticker:    ORCL.andO;Topic:     StockSoftware PublishersFinancial Stability.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>